This isn't a bug or anything, so apologies for opening an issue, but given the ubiquitousness of this pattern, I thought it reasonable to try and get some sort of official stance on the subject, hence the issue.

So here's a very common pattern to do a thing after a response:

```js
const responseTime = (_, res, next) => {
    function finish() {
        // calculate time taken for request
        const [seconds, nanoseconds] = process.hrtime(startAt);
        const milliseconds = seconds * 1e3 + nanoseconds * 1e-6;
        res.locals['responseTime'] = milliseconds;
    }

    // cleanup to remove memory leaks(???)
    function cleanup() {
        res.removeListener('finish', finish);
        res.removeListener('error', cleanup);
        res.removeListener('close', cleanup);
    }

    res.once('finish', finish);
    res.once('error', cleanup);
    res.once('close', cleanup);

    next();
};
```

[Random real world example of this in the wild](https://github.com/instructure/canvas-rce-api/blob/master/app/middleware/stats.js) - this was the first result i grabbed, I've seen this pattern in a bunch of codebases: https://grep.app/search?q=res.removeListener%28&filter%5Blang%5D%5B0%5D=TypeScript&filter%5Blang%5D%5B1%5D=JavaScript

My question is - is this just cargo cult? Or does this more minimal version work?

```js
const responseTime = (_, res, next) => {
    const startAt = process.hrtime();

    res.once('finish', () => {
        // calculate time taken for request
        const [seconds, nanoseconds] = process.hrtime(startAt);
        const milliseconds = seconds * 1e3 + nanoseconds * 1e-6;
        res.locals['responseTime'] = milliseconds;
    });

    next();
};
```

The fear is "memory leaks" might be an issue if the .finish handler never executes (client drops the connection early) and so the function is never dropped from memory - but is this actually a concern since I assume the whole res object and all child nodes will be thrown away and GC'd?

