I believe this is not desirable for 99% of the developers.

From [official doc on error handling](https://expressjs.com/en/guide/error-handling.html):

> For errors returned from asynchronous functions invoked by route handlers and middleware, **you must pass them to the next() function**, where Express will catch and process them.

Basically developers have to repeat this in all async handlers:

```
app.get('/', async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    await someAsyncFunc();
  } catch (err) {
    next(err);
  }
});
```

To prevent repeating the code, the best I can do is to use [express-async-handler](https://github.com/Abazhenov/express-async-handler), which is basically a wrapper to do the above:

```
const asyncHandler = require('express-async-handler');

app.get('/', asyncHandler(async (req, res, next) => {
  await someAsyncFunc();
}));
```

In synchronous handler, exceptions are already auto-handled by Express. Is there any reason we do not do the same in async case? Why ask user to explicitly do this repeatedly themselves?

If there is no specific reason, I would suggest auto-handling async exception as a feature request.

